title: For Sale:  FN49 Belgium Masterpiece of a Rifle
postcontent:
The FN-49  The Last Elegant Old-World Military Rifle. 
Caliber: 7.92x57mm (8mm Mauser) 
Action: Gas operated, tilting bolt 
Overall length: 45.5 inches 
Barrel length: 22 inches 
Weight: 9.2 lbs 
Magazine: 10 rounds, non-detachable 

The SAFN-49 rifle (Semi-Automatic, FN, model of 1949) was developed by the famous Belgian company Fabrique Nationale Herstal. Nicknamed the "Cadillac" of Battle Rifles because it was so expensive to produce. Almost Every part is robust and billet machined. It is the rifle from which the famous FN FAL rifle originated.

This particular Rifle is an Egyptian Contract 8mm Mauser. The 8mm is the equivalent to a 32 caliber bullet, making it larger in diameter than a 308 or 30.06. Additionally, the bullet of standard load is 196 grains in weight, about 25% heavier than standard 308 or 30.06 load.

The SAFN-49 is a gas operated, semi-automatic, magazine fed rifle with a 10 round magazine. It uses a short-piston stroke gas drive, with gas camber and a gas piston-tappet located above the barrel. The gas piston has its own separate return spring. The tilting bolt is linked to the bolt carrier, and tilts down to lock into the floor of the milled steel receiver. Charging handle is mounted at the right side of the bolt carrier and reciprocates when gun is fired. Magazine has a bolt catch which holds the bolt open after the last round from magazine is fired. The gas chamber features a gas regulator which also can be used as a gas cut-off, which is required to fire rifle grenades. Barrel is equipped with muzzle flash hider and a bayonet mount. The single-piece stock is made from wood and has a semi-pistol grip and a separate upper handguard. Front sight is mounted on the gas chamber and is protected by two side "wings", rear sight is of adjustable diopter type and is mounted at the rear of the receiver. The safety switch is located just above the triggerguard at the right side of the gun. When safety is engaged, the safety switch lever protrudes into the triggerguard to interfere with trigger finger, so the state of the safety could be inspected without the single look at it.
 The gun fell victim to the Import assault weapons ban of the early nineties, and few were available.
Century Arms bought a couple hundred and sold them as C&R collectibles, however they were Refinished and were equipt with after market stocks. This rifle is in Excellent Shooting order. Overall a Beautiful Rifle in VERY NICE condition. The Best I have ever seen that wasn't refinished.  All original, except that there was no flash hider. Sometime after I bought the gun, I found the original flash hider at Sarco and bought it.

this beretta pistol was included in a delivery of 65,000 Beretta M1934/35 pistols delivered to the German Army Headquarters in Italy between Aug 1944 and Feb, 1945. Those serial # were 534000/599000.
After the 8 September 1943 armistice between Italy and the Allies, the Germans saddled Beretta with three engineers from Germany. Moreover the factory was GARRISONED BY THE SS! Weapons of that time, even the ones produced for the Germans, bore the punch mark 4UT, (Quarto Ufficio tecnico di Controllo Armi e Munizioni--4th Technnical Control Unit...
-an C. Still, in Axis Pistols, page 107, states,
"It is likely that almost all of the 4/UT, ...were used by the German Army". He also includes two other variations in this statement, "1944 dated and blank slide Model 1935".
Ugo Menchini, in Pietro Beretta Le Automatiche, regarding an M1934, page 255, states,
"In late 1940 there appears an oval including the punch mark IVU. It refers to the 4th technical Control Unit of the FAG, where inspection was carried out."
Note that, while they seem to represent the same inspectors, the "IVU" is not the same mark as the "4UT". The IVU would be found on the pre RSI model M1934, and the 4UT would be found on the RSI model M1935.
These are the reasons why I believe that it is likely that all of the 4UT Berettas WERE RSI pistols!! the IVU and the 4UT were the same office, but under Italian management -the IVU, before the surrender of Italy, and German the 4UT, so after september, 8 1943.

pistol is in near unissued condition and a prime example of strain on axis weapons fabrication late in the war, with tooling and machinery marks throughout, it comes with one extra original period magazine.   - 720 620 78 84  call txt

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson M&P 22 Handgun, Case, Mags
postcontent:
It's a visual match to the rest of the S&W M&P lineup but it's actually made by Walther. It's effectively a P22 in drag. Walthesson? Westher? Dunno.

This is a complete kit. One pistol, 3 mags (only comes from the store with 1, we bought 2 more at $50/ea and they're damned near unobtanium right now), documentation, and an action lock. The pistol is cosmetically excellent but the inside of the slide has some light colored areas where the anodizing is wearing some. Round count is about 1200, which for a .22 is roughly like saying "one weekend of playing around". Feed it CCI MiniMags and it runs perfectly. Feed it dirty, sticky Walmart ammo and it'll have a failure to eject about once every 50 rounds. Always clears perfectly with a single rack of the slide. Hey, it's made by Walther, and we all know they're picky about ammo. 

I love my centerfire M&Ps and this was supposed to be my cheap practice gun. For whatever reason, I failed to bond with this gun. I can't say there's anything wrong with it, I just don't love it so it has to go.

We've got $500 in the gun and the mags, so I'd like to get $375 out of it since you won't have to pay tax or transfer on it.
